Titanic Association Rule

The Titanic Dataset

The Titanic dataset is used in this example, which can be downloaded as “titanic.raw.rdata” at the Data page.

Survived=No, Survived=Yes

We then set rhs=c(“Survived=No”, “Survived=Yes”) in appearance to make sure that only “Survived=No” and “Survived=Yes” will appear in the rhs of rules.

rules <- apriori(titanic.raw,
                 parameter = list(minlen=2, supp=0.005,
                                  conf=0.8),
                 appearance = list(rhs=c("Survived=No", "Survived=Yes"),
                                   default="lhs"),
                 control = list(verbose=F))
rules.sorted <- sort(rules, by="lift")
inspect(rules.sorted)

Prune Rules

# find redundant rules
subset.matrix <- is.subset(rules.sorted, rules.sorted)
subset.matrix[lower.tri(subset.matrix, diag=T)] <- NA
x[.] <- val: x is “ngTMatrix”, val not in {TRUE, FALSE} is coerced; NA |--> TRUE.
redundant <- colSums(subset.matrix, na.rm=T) >= 1
which(redundant)
            {Class=2nd,Age=Child,Survived=Yes} 
                                             1

                                             2 
           {Class=1st,Sex=Female,Survived=Yes}

# remove redundant rules
rules.pruned <- rules.sorted[!redundant]
inspect(rules.pruned)
